Data Structure¶

There are 10,000 customers in the bank's client base, each with 13 features. This analytics use 10 indepedent variables and 1 depedent variable to understand patterns in the data.

Main features of interest¶

I'm interested in determing what features predic customer churn.

Features that would support investigation¶

I expect that bank balance, credit score, age,number of products, and estimated salary to have strong effect on churn. while gender, and tenure have little to no effect on exiting.

Univariate Exploration¶

How is account balance distributed in the client base?¶

Understanding balance distribution will guide the direction of this investigation since from a business perspective this is an important factor in identifying churning clients.

In [7]:
#sns.set_style('darkgrid')
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
binsize=15000
bins=np.arange(0, data['balance'].max()+1000, binsize)
plt.hist(data=data,x='balance', bins=bins);
plt.xlabel('balance ($)');
plt.title('Account Balance Distribution');

Account balance is bimodal distribution with the highest peak at 0.00, and the second distribution is a normal distribution with a peak between 100k and 150k.

log_binsize = 0.15
bins =10** np.arange(0, np.log10(data['estimatedsalary'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = data, x = 'estimatedsalary', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([5e2,1e3, 6e3,10e3,20e3, 50e3,150e3,300e3], ['500','1k', '6k', '10k','20k', '50k','150k','300k'])

plt.title('Salary Distribution on log Scale')
plt.show()

What proportion owns credit card ?¶

Credit card is a profit generating tool for the bank, identifying these proportions could help the bank make critical decisions. If those who do not own card are way more than those who have card, the bank could investigate why and perhaps come up with deals/promos to attract more card owners from the existing client base.

In [12]:
churn=data['exited']
labs={0:'Retained', 1:'Churned'}
props=churn.value_counts().index.map(labs)
explode=(0.1,0)
plt.gcf().set_size_inches(18, 8)
churn.value_counts().plot(kind='pie',ylabel='',labels=props ,autopct='%.0f%%',textprops={'size': 'large'},shadow=True,explode=explode);
plt.title('Proportions of Churned and Retained Clients', size=15)
plt.show()

20 percent of the client base quit business with the bank and 80% are still doing business with the bank.

How is age, and balance distributed by churn status and number of products?¶

compared to box plot above, Violin plot could cleary show how balance and age is distributed by churn status and number of products.

In [28]:
fig, ax=plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(10,10))
sns.violinplot(data=data, y='balance', x='exited',ax=ax[0,0], palette=color)
ax[0,0].set_yticks([0, 5e4,100e3,150e3,200e3, 300e3]);
ax[0,0].set_xticks([0,1],['Retained', 'Churned'])
ax[0,0].set_yticklabels([0, '50k','100k','150k','200k', '300k']);
ax[0,0].set_title('Balance by churn status')
ax[0,0].set_xlabel('Churn status')

sns.violinplot(data=data, y='balance', x='numofproducts',ax=ax[0,1],palette=color)
ax[0,1].set_yticks([0, 5e4,100e3,150e3,200e3, 300e3]);
ax[0,1].set_yticklabels([0, '50k','100k','150k','200k', '300k']);
ax[0,1].set_title('Balance by number of products')
ax[0,1].set_title('Balance by number of products')
ax[0,1].set_xlabel('Number of products')

sns.violinplot(data=data, y='age',x='exited', ax=ax[1,0],palette=color);
ax[1,0].set_title('Age by Churn Status')
ax[1,0].set_xticks([0,1],['Retained', 'Churned'])
ax[1,0].set_xlabel('Churn status')
sns.violinplot(data=data, y='age',x='numofproducts', ax=ax[1,1],palette=color);
ax[1,1].set_title('Age by number of products')
ax[1,1].set_xlabel('Number of products')
plt.show()

Churned clients have slightly higher bank account balance than their counterparts. Majority of clients who stay have a 0.00 account balance. Clients with 2 products have the least account balance, and the largest proportion of them have 0.00 balance while those with 4 products have the highest balance and very few of them have 0.00 balance. Clients with 1 product have high account balance and majority have a balance between 100k and 150k while very few have 0.00 account balance.

large proportion of churned clients are about 40-50 years old. The oldest churned clients is 70 years. most of the retained clients are 30-40 years and the oldest slightly below 60 years. clients with 1 and 2 products are on average slightly below 40 years probably because very few from these groups churned. Clients with 3 and 4 products are on average slightly above 40 years probably because most of churned clients are from these two groups, this confirms that churned clients are about 40-50 years, the bank should watch this clients 40+ years and maybe come up with products or deals that might retain these clients.

Also for churned clients balance declines with increase in the number of products but clients with 4 products show a different behavior, their balance is relatively higher. All through it is observed that clients with 4 products are special in a way.
